DESIGN
## Plan

**Approach:** Make the epic-close holistic docs/reality reconciliation a HARD GATE via A+B (a concrete make target + a promoted mandatory checklist/runbook gate), scoped honestly to the thin real delta. `bd` emits no mechanical epic-close event (epic close is the operator action `bd close <epic>` / `bd epic close-eligible`; `bd close` has no pre-close plugin hook), so the "hard gate" is a one-command pass/fail check the documented workflow REQUIRES to exit 0 before `bd close <epic>` — not a literal pre-close hook. The mechanical reconciliation an epic close needs is ALREADY almost entirely covered by the existing whole-surface checks: `make docs-reality` (builds etude fresh; every shipped command is advertised in README usage + named in the docs/README index + has a docs/cli page; no orphan pages; no docs/plans claim a shipped command is unimplemented) and `make docs-check` (diffs generated docs/cli). So rather than build per-epic command-set machinery that would duplicate `docs-reality`, add a thin `make reconcile` target that composes those two checks (one mechanical pass/fail), and promote the checklist+runbook language from `[PLANNED]`/suggested to a MANDATORY epic-close gate that names the exact command. Honest delta: see below.

**Honest delta over per-bead docs-reality/docs-check:** Small but real. `make docs-reality` already runs against the WHOLE shipped CLI inventory (not just the bead's command), so per-bead runs already catch "a command shipped by the epic is missing from README/index/cli page." The genuine epic-close value is (1) RE-running the whole-surface check once at the integration point after ALL sibling beads have landed — catching cross-bead drift no single bead's pre-merge check saw (e.g. a bead whose docs-reality ran green before a later sibling's command landed, or a bead closed with `--force` past its gate), and (2) a consolidated human README/docs-index narrative review (does the index still read coherently across everything the epic shipped; does docs/README still explain why user-facing docs are sparse) that no mechanical check covers. This is a thin-delta situation, so the deliverable is deliberately a compose-existing-checks target + a promoted prose gate, NOT new machinery.

**Deliverable 1 — `make reconcile` target (Makefile):** A `.PHONY` target named `reconcile` that runs `make docs-reality` then `make docs-check` (composition, so it inherits their fresh-build + drift detection and FAILS non-zero if either fails). It is a real check that can fail on drift: it fails when any shipped command is missing from README usage, the docs/README index, or a docs/cli page; when an orphan docs/cli page names a non-existent command; when a docs/plans line calls a shipped command unimplemented; or when generated docs/cli is stale vs source. Add `reconcile` to the existing `.PHONY` line. Keep it a thin recipe (`$(MAKE) docs-reality && $(MAKE) docs-check`) so it composes rather than duplicates; no scripts/ helper is needed because the genuine mechanical delta over the two existing checks is nil.

**Deliverable 2 — mandatory checklist gate (docs/plans/dogfood/docs-checklist.md):** Add a new "Epic-Close Reconciliation (MANDATORY)" section, phrased as a hard MUST (not [PLANNED]): before `bd close <epic>` (or `bd epic close-eligible`), you MUST run `make reconcile` and it MUST exit 0; resolve every finding (or add a justified suppression to scripts/docs-reality-allow.txt for genuinely-planned prose) before closing. Plus the one human step the mechanical check can't do: read README.md + docs/README.md once holistically and confirm the full set of commands the epic shipped reads coherently end-to-end and docs/README still explains why user-facing docs are sparse. This replaces the current implicit per-bead-only framing in the "Mechanical reality check" / Final Review sections; cross-reference it from those sections so per-bead `make docs-reality` and epic-close `make reconcile` are clearly distinct steps.

**Deliverable 3 — runbook gate wording (docs/plans/dogfood/review-gate-runbook.md):** Add an "Epic-Close Gate" note expressing the hard requirement in the runbook's gate vocabulary: closing an epic is a gated action; the gate is `make reconcile` exiting 0 plus the holistic README/index read; record it like other gate attempts (one-line note on the epic naming the command result + commit/SHA, consistent with the existing close-reason convention). State plainly that this is a workflow-required mechanical command, not a bd pre-close hook (bd has none), so the enforcement is the documented MUST + the target's pass/fail.

