**Tests / Verification:**
- Passes on clean tree: `make reconcile` exits 0 today (verified: `make docs-reality` -> "OK - 10 commands"; `make docs-check` -> clean diff).
- Fails on injected drift (the real "can it fail" check, no built-binary smoke needed since no product binary behavior changes):
  - Inject a missing-command-in-README drift in a throwaway copy / git stash sandbox (e.g. temporarily remove an `etude <cmd>` README usage line) and confirm `make reconcile` exits non-zero listing the finding, then restore.
  - Inject a generated-docs drift (touch a docs/cli page) and confirm `make reconcile` fails via the docs-check leg, then restore.
  - Confirm it fails for the RIGHT reason in each case (the failing leg names the drift), not a spurious error.
- Lint: `make lint` (gofmt/go vet) unaffected; Makefile/docs changes don't touch Go.
- Doc-self-consistency: after editing the dogfood docs, run `make reconcile` itself to confirm the new prose introduces no stale-claim false positive (e.g. no new docs/plans line trips the shipped-command stale scan).

**Docs:** This bead IS the docs/process change (checklist + runbook + ledger). No generated CLI reference change (no command added). docs/README index unaffected (no new shipped command). The retro-ledger C1 line flip is the closing-the-loop doc update.

**Risks:** Low. (1) Thin delta — be explicit in the prose that `make reconcile` mostly re-runs the per-bead whole-surface checks at the integration point; do not oversell it as catching something fundamentally new. (2) Enforcement is documentary (a required MUST + a pass/fail target), not a hard technical block, because bd has no pre-close hook — state this honestly rather than implying mechanical prevention. (3) Avoid duplicating docs-reality logic in a new script (would drift from the canonical check) — compose, don't copy.

**Recommended gate tier:** Tier 3 (single-seat in-harness Opus). Justification: NO shipping-code change — a thin Makefile target composing two existing checks plus docs/checklist/runbook prose. Per the runbook, Tier 3 is for "changes with NO shipping-code change: ... docs/planning-notes-only changes." Escalation rule still applies: if review finds the `reconcile` target subtly alters product behavior or touches a Tier-1 surface (it does not), rerun at Tier 1. Compose with the lightweight-artifact framing (narrow the gate to the changed Makefile + doc diffs).

